1.2.1.Categorical variables¶

In [6]:
def category_type(df):
    df['symboling']=df['symboling'].astype('category')
    df['fuel-type']=df['fuel-type'].astype('category')
    df['make']=df['make'].astype('category')
    df['aspiration']=df['aspiration'].astype('category')
    df['num-of-doors']=df['num-of-doors'].astype('category')
    df['body-style']=df['body-style'].astype('category')
    df['drive-wheels']=df['drive-wheels'].astype('category')
    df['engine-location']=df['engine-location'].astype('category')
    df['engine-type']=df['engine-type'].astype('category')
    df['num-of-cylinders']=df['num-of-cylinders'].astype('category')
    df['fuel-system']=df['fuel-system'].astype('category')
    return(df)

df=category_type(df)
In [7]:
cat_var={}
categories= list((df.select_dtypes(include=['category'])))

for x in categories:
    cat_var[x]=df[x].unique()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(sharex=True,nrows=4, ncols=3,figsize=(20,30))
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=.5)
for idx, key in enumerate(cat_var):
    for value in cat_var[key]:
        subset= df[df[key] == value]
        ax_coord = plt.subplot(4, 3, idx+1)
        sns.distplot(subset['price'], hist = False, ax= ax_coord, kde = True,kde_kws = {'linewidth': 3},label = value) 
    ax_coord.legend(fontsize=10,title = key,ncol=2)
    ax_coord.set_title('Price distribution per %s level'% key)
    ax_coord.set_xlabel('Price')
    ax_coord.set_ylabel('Density')
    fig.delaxes(plt.subplot(4,3,12))
plt.show()

These plots allow us to understand the impact of each variable on the price of a car. Many conclusions can be driven from just looking at those graphs, for instance:

  • The price distribution is different for each level of the symboling variable, which leads us to think there is a correlation, or an impact, of the symboling variable on the price of the car.
  • On the contrary, the price distribution is similar no matter if a car has 2 or 4 doors, thus leaving us thinking that this won't be a good explanatory variable in our model.

Thus in order to make more efficient we will be able to group certain levels together, such as:

  • rwd and fwd who have a very similar price distribution, whereas the third level 4wd has a price distribution that is significantly different.
  • Same could be applied to the make variable, which is pretty messy and surely needs some level aggregation.
  • It is quite hard to estimate if certain levels statistically differ with each other:
    • In engine-type ohc and ohcf are almost perfectly superposed,
    • same for dohc and l.

def numeric_type(df):
    df['normalized-losses']=pd.to_numeric(df['normalized-losses'],'coerce')
    df['wheel-base']=pd.to_numeric(df['wheel-base'],'coerce')
    df['length']=pd.to_numeric(df['length'],'coerce')
    df['width']=pd.to_numeric(df['width'],'coerce')
    df['height']=pd.to_numeric(df['height'],'coerce')
    df['curb-weight']=pd.to_numeric(df['curb-weight'],'coerce')
    df['engine-size']=pd.to_numeric(df['engine-size'],'coerce')
    df['bore']=pd.to_numeric(df['bore'],'coerce')
    df['stroke']=pd.to_numeric(df['stroke'],'coerce')
    df['compression-ratio']=pd.to_numeric(df['compression-ratio'],'coerce')
    df['horsepower']=pd.to_numeric(df['horsepower'],'coerce')
    df['peak-rpm']=pd.to_numeric(df['peak-rpm'],'coerce')
    df['city-mpg']=pd.to_numeric(df['city-mpg'],'coerce')
    df['highway-mpg']=pd.to_numeric(df['highway-mpg'],'coerce')
    return(df)

df=numeric_type(df)
In [9]:
cont_var=list(df.select_dtypes(include=['int','float']))
#['normalized-losses','wheel-base','length','width','height','curb-weight','engine-size','bore','stroke','compression-ratio','horsepower','peak-rpm','city-mpg','highway-mpg']

fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=5, ncols=3,figsize=(20,20))
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=.5)
for idx, var in enumerate(cont_var):
    ax_coord = plt.subplot(5, 3, idx+1)
    sns.regplot(x="price", y=var, data=df)
    ax_coord.set_title('Price Vs. %s relationship'% var)
    ax_coord.set_xlabel('Price')
    ax_coord.set_ylabel(var)
    fig.delaxes(plt.subplot(5,3,15))
plt.show()

In the predecessing graph we see the relationship the price has with other continuous variables.

  • We see some linear relationship with:
    • curb-weight, engine-size, horsepower, city-mpg and highway-mpg
    • tends to make sense from a business perspective as you would assume the bigger and/or the more powerfull a car is the more expensive it is. There also could be a strong correlation between city-mpg and highway-mpg.
  • I would assume a logarithmic relationship with the length and width of car and its price. This could also be explained from a business perspective since a majority of car fall within the same length range, but when they are longer they are more expensive (eg: limo)
  • Other variables such as stroke or compression-ratio have less obvious relationships. Only a correlation testing would confirm the assumption.

3.Building the models¶

Since we are given only a few observations (around 200), I will run the model without and with feature engineering, I expect the different evaluation metrics to not be completely different, and the two models to perform overall almost the same.

rf=RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=500, 
                             criterion='mse')

gb=GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=500, 
                             criterion='mse')

x_=np.asarray(df_dum[features])
y_=np.asarray(df_dum['price'])

3.2.Evaluation metrics¶

In [17]:
mse_rf=[]
rmse_rf=[]
score_rf=[]
mse_gb=[]
rmse_gb=[]
score_gb=[]

for i in range (10):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = model_selection.train_test_split(x_, y_, test_size=0.1)
    fitted_rf=rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    fitted_gb=gb.fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse_rf.append(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test,fitted_rf.predict(X_test)))
    rmse_rf.append(math.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test,fitted_rf.predict(X_test))))
    score_rf.append(rf.score(X_train, y_train))
    mse_gb.append(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test,fitted_gb.predict(X_test)))
    rmse_gb.append(math.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test,fitted_gb.predict(X_test))))
    score_gb.append(gb.score(X_train, y_train))
In [18]:
f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2,figsize=(20,10))
ax1.plot(rmse_rf,label='Random Forest')
ax1.plot(rmse_gb,label='Gradient Boosting')
ax2.plot(score_rf,label='Random Forest')
ax2.plot(score_gb,label='Gradient Boosting')
ax1.legend(loc='upper left')
ax2.legend(loc='upper left')
ax1.set_title('RMSE comparison')
ax2.set_title('R-square comparison')
plt.show()

3.3.Model without 'normalized-losses'¶

We have seen earlier that 'normalized-losses' has a lot of NAs. Removing that variable would allow to run the model on more observations.

We can also assume that this variable is not always available, hence the need of creating a model without it.

In [19]:
#new dataset without variable 
df_dum_bis=df.copy()
df_dum_bis=feature_keep(df_dum_bis)
df_dum_bis=df_dum_bis.drop('normalized-losses',axis=1)
df_dum_bis=df_dum_bis.dropna()

#new set of features 
features_bis=list(df_dum_bis.columns)
features_bis.remove('price')
x_bis=np.asarray(df_dum_bis[features_bis])
y_bis=np.asarray(df_dum_bis['price'])

#new metrics
mse_rf_bis=[]
rmse_rf_bis=[]
score_rf_bis=[]
mse_gb_bis=[]
rmse_gb_bis=[]
score_gb_bis=[]

for i in range (10):
    X_train_bis, X_test_bis, y_train_bis, y_test_bis = model_selection.train_test_split(x_bis, y_bis, test_size=0.1)
    fitted_rf_bis=rf.fit(X_train_bis, y_train_bis)
    fitted_gb_bis=gb.fit(X_train_bis, y_train_bis)
    mse_rf_bis.append(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test_bis,fitted_rf_bis.predict(X_test_bis)))
    rmse_rf_bis.append(math.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test_bis,fitted_rf_bis.predict(X_test_bis))))
    score_rf_bis.append(rf.score(X_train_bis, y_train_bis))
    mse_gb_bis.append(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test_bis,fitted_gb_bis.predict(X_test_bis)))
    rmse_gb_bis.append(math.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test_bis,fitted_gb_bis.predict(X_test_bis))))
    score_gb_bis.append(gb.score(X_train_bis, y_train_bis))

#new metrics plots
f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2,figsize=(20,10))
ax1.plot(rmse_rf_bis,label='Random Forest without NL')
ax1.plot(rmse_gb_bis,label='Gradient Boosting without NL')
ax2.plot(score_rf_bis,label='Random Forest without NL')
ax2.plot(score_gb_bis,label='Gradient Boosting without NL')
ax1.legend(loc='upper left')
ax2.legend(loc='upper left')
ax1.set_title('RMSE comparison')
ax2.set_title('R-square comparison')
plt.show()

The models do not seem to perform differently with or without the removed variable. The small differences in the metrics are explained by the train and test split.

3.4.Feature importance¶

In [20]:
features = list(df_dum.columns)
importances_rf = rf.feature_importances_[rf.feature_importances_>0.001]
indices_rf = np.argsort(importances_rf)

importances_gb = gb.feature_importances_[gb.feature_importances_>0.001]
indices_gb = np.argsort(importances_gb)

f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2,figsize=(20,10))
ax1.set_title('RF Feature Importances')
ax1.barh(range(len(indices_rf)), importances_rf[indices_rf], color='b', align='center')
ax1.set_yticks(range(len(indices_rf)))
ax1.set_yticklabels([features[i] for i in indices_rf])
ax1.set_xlabel('Relative Importance')
ax2.set_title('GB Feature Importances')
ax2.barh(range(len(indices_gb)), importances_gb[indices_gb], color='b', align='center')
ax2.set_yticks(range(len(indices_gb)))
ax2.set_yticklabels([features[i] for i in indices_gb])
ax2.set_xlabel('Relative Importance')
plt.show()
